> Could you clarify what you mean by this? What is "the interpreted PATH construct"? How would we use "containment with the original variable"?

Yeah, sure. Now when you run `shellenv` you'll get something like this:

```
export HOMEBREW_CELLAR="/opt/homebrew/Cellar";
export HOMEBREW_REPOSITORY="/opt/homebrew";
PATH="/opt/homebrew/bin:/opt/homebrew/sbin:/Users/runner/.cargo/~~~~~~sr/appleinternal/bin"; export PATH;
[ -z "${MANPATH-}" ] || export MANPATH=":${MANPATH#:}";
export INFOPATH="/opt/homebrew/share/info:${INFOPATH:-}";
```

While more common way is to use next:
```
export HOMEBREW_CELLAR="/opt/homebrew/Cellar";
export HOMEBREW_REPOSITORY="/opt/homebrew";
export PATH="/opt/homebrew/bin:/opt/homebrew/sbin:$PATH"
```

But as @Bo98 described here we hit users of `bash -u` somehow this way.
